'''Mildred Ellen Methvin''', known as '''Mimi Methvin''' (born October 24, 1952),<ref name=voterportal>{{cite web|url=https://voterportal.sos.la.gov/home.aspx?galogin=voter|title=Mildred Methvin, October 1952|publisher=[[Louisiana  Secretary of State]]|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> is an [[alternative dispute resolution]] [[Mediation|mediator]] in [[Lafayette, Louisiana|Lafayette]], [[Louisiana]].<ref name=aboutsatori>{{cite web|url=http://satoriadr.com/Files/Press/PressReleaseJuly.pdf|title=Press Release: Retirement of Judge Mildred Methvin|publisher=satoriadr.com|date=July 28, 2009|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref>   From 1983 to 2009, she was the [[United States Magistrate Judge]] for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Louisiana|Western District of Louisiana]]. In 2014, she became the short-term interim judge of the Louisiana 27th Judicial District Court, Division 
D, in [[St. Landry Parish, Louisiana|St. Landry Parish]].<ref name=dailyworld/>


==Background==

Named for her maternal grandmother, Mildred Rosalind Hill Cunningham (1901-1982), Methvin is descended from a pioneer political family with roots in [[Natchitoches, Louisiana|Natchitoches]], [[Castor, Louisiana|Castor]], and her native [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria]], Louisiana. Her maternal great-great-grandfather, [[Milton Joseph Cunningham]], was a member of both houses of the [[Louisiana State Legislature]] and for three terms prior to 1900 the [[Attorney General of Louisiana]].<ref name=mimimethvin>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.com/users/m/e/t/Mildred-Methvin/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0108.html|title=Milton Joseph Cunningham|publisher=genealogy.com|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>Her great-grandfather, [[Charles Milton Cunningham]], was the editor of ''The Natchitoches Times'' and a member of the [[Louisiana State Senate]] from 1915 to 1922.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://senate.la.gov/Documents/Membership/Documents/SenateMembership1880ForwardRevisedMar2011.pdf|title=Membership in the Louisiana Senate, 1880-Present|publisher=senate.la.gov|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/m/e/t/Mildred-Methvin/index.html|title=Charles Milton Cunningham|publisher=familytreemaker.genealogy.com|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> A great-uncle, [[William Tharp Cunningham]], served one term in the [[Louisiana House of Representatives]] from [[Natchitoches Parish]] from 1908 to 1912, prior to becoming a judge.<ref name=house/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.com/users/m/e/t/Mildred-Methvin/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0185.html|title=William Tharp Cunningham|publisher=genealogy.com|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> 

Her grandfather, [[W. Peyton Cunningham]], husband of the former Mildred Hill, was a lawyer and a member of the Louisiana House from Natchitoches Parish from 1932 to 1940.<ref name=house>{{cite web|url=http://house.louisiana.gov/H_PDFdocs/HouseMembership_History_CURRENT.pdf|title=Membership in the Louisiana House of Representatives, 1812-2016: Natchitoches  Parish|publisher=house.Louisiana.gov|accessdate=September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.genealogy.com/users/m/e/t/Mildred-Methvin/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0094.html|title=William Peyton Cunningham, Sr.|publisher=genealogy.com|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>Her father, [[Myrtis Methvin|DeWitt T. Methvin, Jr.]], was an Alexandria lawyer prominent in both legal and civic circles. Her mother, Lallah Hill Cunningham Methvin (1929-2012), was the daughter of W. Peyton Cunningham<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=121114950|title=Lallah Hill Cunningham Methvin|publisher=findagrave.com|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref> and the first wife of DeWitt Methvin and the mother of his five children, including Mildred Methvin's four siblings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.com/users/m/e/t/Mildred-Methvin/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0001.html|title=DeWitt Talmage Methvin, Jr.|publisher=genealogy.com|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> Her paternal grandmother, [[Myrtis Methvin]], a native of [[Attala County, Mississippi|Attala County]] in central [[Mississippi]], was from 1933 to 1945 the [[mayor]] of Castor in [[Bienville Parish, Louisiana|Bienville Parish]] in northwestern Louisiana and the second woman in Louisiana history to serve as a town mayor. Her paternal grandfather, DeWitt Methvin, Sr. (1894-1975), was also a Mississippi native, a timber salesman and a member of the Bienville Parish Police Jury, the parish governing body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.com/users/m/e/t/Mildred-Methvin/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0010.html|title=Myrtis Lucille Gregory Methvin|author=Mildred "Mimi" Methvin McManus|location=[[Lafayette, Louisiana|Lafayette]], [[Louisiana]]|publisher=genealogy.com|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>

Methvin was reared in Alexandria and spent her formative period as well on [[Cane River Lake]] in Natchitoches with her Cunningham family members. A [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]], Methvin graduated in 1970 from [[Holy Savior Menard Central High School]] in Alexandria. She then attended [[H. Sophie Newcomb Memorial College]] in [[New Orleans]] for three years before enrolling in [[Tulane University]] Law School her senior. She was inducted into [[Phi Beta Kappa]] upon graduation from Newcomb in 1974 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[Philosophy]]. The summer before law school, she was an intern in the Washington, D.C. office of U.S. Representative Gillis Long. Methvin later transferred and received her law degree in 1976 from [[Georgetown University Law Center]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=aboutsatori/>

==Legal career==

While in law school in the District of Columbia, Methvin worked in the office of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[United States Representative]] [[Gillis William Long]] of [[Louisiana's 8th congressional district]], disbanded in 1993. She subsequently worked from 1977 to 1979 as an associate attorney for her father's law office, Gist, Methvin, Hughes & Munsterman in Alexandria, the Gist being [[Howard B. Gist, Jr.]] From 1979 to 1981, she was an assistant United States attorney for the Western District of Louisiana, based in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]].<ref name=dailyworld/> In 1983, Methvin was named United States Magistrate Judge, with jurisdiction over civil and criminal cases, including violations of federal [[game law]], for the United States District Court in Lafayette. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nadn.org/PDF/Mimi-Methvin.pdf|title=Mildred E. "Mimi" Methvin|publisher=nadn.org|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>

In 1990 she was organizational chair of the    [[American Inns of Court]] of Acadiana, serving as its president in 1995. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.innsofcourt.org/media/41140/americaninnofcourtofacadianamemberdirectory.pdf|title=American Inns of Court Membership Directory|publisher=home.innsofcourt.org|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>In 1996, she helped found a second Inn, the John M. Duhe, Jr. American Inn of Court. In 1997, [[William H. Rehnquist]], then [[Chief Justice of the United States]], appointed Methvin as one of only three magistrate judges in the country to the select committee which makes national policy governing the activities of federal magistrate judges. Magistrate Judge Methvin presided over numerous civil jury and non-jury trials as well as [[felony]] pretrial matters, including [[arraignment]], [[bail]], and [[Detention (imprisonment)|detention]] hearings. She accepted guilty pleas, issued [[search warrant]]s and [[arrest warrant]]s, and selected [[grand jury]] members.<ref She successfully settled close to a thousand civil cases during her tenure, and sentenced thousands of [[defendant]]s under the [[Migratory Bird Treaty Act]] and the National Wildlife Refuge Act.

In 2009, Methvin retired as magistrate judge instead to open her own conflict resolution office in Lafayette, which she still maintains. From 2011 to 2013, Methvin served part-time as a Recall U.S. Magistrate Judge for the federal courts in [[Pennsylvania]] and [[Maryland]]. In the summer of 2014, she was appointed by the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]] to a nearly six-month tenure as interim judge of the Louisiana 27th Judicial District Court based in [[Opelousas, Louisiana|Opelousas]] in St. Landry Parish. She succeeded Judge Donald Hebert, who died in office.<ref name=dailyworld>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyworld.com/story/news/2014/07/17/mildred-methvin-to-fill-judge-heberts-position/12759855/|title=Mildred Methvin to fill Judge Hebert's position|author=William Johnson|date=July 16, 2014|publisher=''Opelousas Daily World''|location=[[Opelousas, Louisiana|Opelousas]], [[Louisiana]]|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>

==Family life==

In 1988, Methvin married James Thomas McManus (born February 1951) of Lafayette, and the couple had two sons, Michael James McManus and Connor Hill McManus.  McManus had three other children from his former marriage to Dianne Hatten: Christine Lynn McManus, Matthew Robert McManus, and John Thomas McManus, who hence became Methvin's stepchildren.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.com/users/m/e/t/Mildred-Methvin/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0079.html|title=James Thomas McManus|publisher=genealogy.com|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>The couple divorced in 2006.

Methvin is also heavily involved in the study of her family [[genealogy]].<ref name=mimimethvin/>

